pr_description:
# Summary

this extends graphql-typescript-request template to allow users to pass a custom wrapper for generated sdk actions. 

the intention is to allow things like adding retry policies or request logging/profiling to the generated sdk calls.

the intention is to make a small, non-breaking change that can implement something like middleware.

related #3574 

# Usage

## default usage

by default, no extra config is needed and no breaking changes to generated code will be made.

`getSdk(client)` can still be called as before, and the wrapper will default to the identity function. in other words, the wrapper will just be a passthrough to the original graphql client request (NO-OP).

## passing a custom wrapper

if the consumer wishes to customize request handing behavior, they can pass a `SdkFunctionWrapper`-typed function as the second parameter of `getSdk`:

```
  // example of adding a client timing wrapper
  const client = new GraphQLClient('');
  const clientTimingWrapper: SdkFunctionWrapper = async <T>(action: () => Promise<T>): Promise<T> => {
    const startTime = new Date();
    const result = await action();
    console.log('request duration (ms)', new Date() - startTime)
    return result;
  }

  const sdk = getSdk(client, clientTimingWrapper);
```

## passing a retry wrapper

This example uses [polly-js](https://github.com/mauricedb/polly-js) to define a failure retry wrapper. (this is the use case for which i originally intended to add this capability)

```
const withRetries: RetryWrapper = <T>(action: () => Promise<T>) =>
  polly()
    .handle((err: Error) => {
      warn('GraphqlClient:NetworkError', err);
      return err.message.includes('connect ETIMEDOUT');
    })
    .waitAndRetry(3)
    .executeForPromise(info => {
      if (info.count === 3) {
        error('GraphqlClient:MaxRetries', null, {
          ...info,
          action: action.toString(),
        });
      } else if (info.count > 0) {
        warn('GraphqlClient:RetryingCall', null, {
          ...info,
          action: action.toString(),
        });
      }

      return action();
    });

const sdk = getSdk(client, withRetries);
```

# TODO

- [x] Documentation updates. No no configuration has been added but would probably be a good idea to add examples to the docs. Agree?
- [x] Additional tests if possible to execute wrappers. @dotansimha is there a way I can actually EXECUTE generated code in the context of a unit test?

